          <p><pb n="1r"/><lb n="1"/><gap precision="low" quantity="4" reason="lost" unit="character"/> phālguna di <num value="15">
              <g type="numeral">10</g>
              <unclear>5</unclear>
            </num> parama-daivata-parama-bhaṭṭāraka mahārājādhirāja-śrī-<unclear>vudha</unclear><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->gu</supplied>pt<supplied reason="lost">e pr̥thivī</supplied><lb break="no" n="2"/>-<supplied reason="lost">patau tat-pā</supplied>da-parigr̥hītasya puṇḍravarddhana-bhuktāv uparika-mahārāja-jayadattasya bhogenānu<unclear>vahamā</unclear><lb break="no" n="3"/>nake <unclear>ko</unclear>ṭi<unclear>varṣṣa</unclear>-viṣaye ca tan-niyuktaka Āyuktaka-bhaṇḍake Adhiṣṭhānādhikaraṇa<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->ṁ</supplied> nagara-śreṣṭhi-ribhu<lb break="no" n="4"/>pāla-sārttha-vāha-vasumittra-prathama-kulika-varadatta-prathama-kāyastha-viprapāla-puroge ca sa<unclear>mv</unclear>y<unclear>a</unclear>vaharati<!-- 
In line A.3 instead of tanniyuktaka āyuktaka, Basak (Agrawala likewise) reads tanniyuktakehāyuktaka. Basak emends to tanniyuktaka ihāyuktaka (or °ke ihā°); Agrawala remarks that this is unnecessary. Does Agrawala want to construe tanniyuktaka in compound with iha? Would be strange. The facsimile is illegible; I follow Bhandarkar. 
--><!-- 
Still in A3, I again follow Bhandarkar in reading bhaṇḍaka. Basak reads śaṇḍaka and notes that it could also be gaṇḍaka (Agrawala likewise). See also line A.4 of %IN00056. 
--><!-- 
For the supplied anusvāra after adhikaraṇa, again see %IN00056, line A.4. 
--></p>
          <p><lb n="5"/>Anena śreṣṭhi-<sic>ri</sic>bhupālena vijñāpitaṁ<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> himavac-chikhare kokāmukha-svāminaḥ catvāraḥ kulya-vāpāḥ <unclear>śve</unclear>ta-va<lb break="no" n="6"/>rāha-svāmino pi sapta kulya-vāpāḥ Asmat-phalāśa<sic>n</sic>sinā pu<sic>n</sic>yābhivr̥ddhaye doṅgāgrāme pūrvvaṁ mayā <lb n="7"/>Apradā Atisr̥ṣṭakās<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> tad aha<sic>n</sic> tat-kṣettra-sāmīpya-bhūmau tayor ādya-kokāmukha-svāmi-śvetavarāha<lb break="no" n="8"/>-svāminor-nā<unclear>ma</unclear>l-liṅga-<unclear>kṣoṇī</unclear>-deva-kula-dvayam etat koṣṭhikā-dvayañ ca kārayitum icchāmy<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> Arhatha vāstuno <lb n="9"/>ṣaṭ-<unclear>kulya</unclear>-vāpān yathā-kraya-maryyādayā dātum iti<!-- 
In A6, Agrawala has asmatphalāśansino instead of °śansinā. Basak's reading is °no, emended to °nā. Bhandarkar translates "hoping for eternal benefit" (qualifying mayā), but where does eternal come from? Basak's translation is "in the hope of benefit to myself." The characters a and sma look quite illegible to me; tpha is quite clear (did Agrawala read śaśvatphala?). 
--><!-- 
About ādya in A7, Bhandarkar (1981:343) notes that it may imply that the gods in question were natural rock formations. He may be right, but to me ādya seems more likely to mean "the above," i.e. to those same gods, sort of like eva. 
--><!-- 
In A8, Basak reads nāmalliṅgam ekaṁ and translates "(and?) one nāmaliṅgam(?)".I follow Bhandarkar, who translates "with the subtile Earth-bowing (in front)". The hyphen may be a typo here. He explains (p343) that the location may have been held to be the one where Varāha pulled the earth out with his tusk, hence the earth is described as liṅga, subtile. Sounds tacky, and he does not explain why nāmat means namat, nor does he emend. I have nothing better though; on the facsimile I can't make out anything before devakula, except the I of svāminor. Agrawala notes that Sircar emends to °liṅgam etad. 
--><!-- 
In A8-9, Basak reads vāstuno saha kulya° and translates "kulyavāpas with vāstu (building-grounds)". Bhandarkar translates "six kulyavāpas of building site." A number would certainly be expected here and I find saha+genitive strange. 
--></p>
          <p>yataḥ pustapāla-viṣṇudatta-vijaya<unclear>nandi</unclear>-sthā<sic>n</sic>u<lb break="no" n="10"/>nandinām avadhāraṇayāvadhr̥tam asty anena himavac-chikhare tayoḥ kokāmukha-svāmi-śvetavarā<unclear>ha</unclear>-svāmi<unclear>noḥ</unclear> <lb n="11"/>Apra<unclear>dāḥ</unclear> kṣetra-kulya-vāpā Ekādaśa dattakās<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> tad-artthañ ceha deva-kula-koṣṭhikā-karaṇe yukta<unclear>m e</unclear>ta<unclear>d vijñā</unclear><lb break="no" n="12"/><unclear>pitaṁ kra</unclear>meṇa tat-kṣe<unclear>ttra</unclear>-sāmīpya-bhūmau vāstu dātum ity anuvr̥tta-tri-dīnārikya-ku<unclear>lya-vā</unclear>pa-vikraya-<unclear>maryyā</unclear>da<pb break="no" n="1v"/><lb break="no" n="13"/><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->yā</supplied> <gap extent="unknown" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> rā kulana <gap extent="unknown" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> <unclear>rā ga ra</unclear> <gap extent="unknown" reason="illegible" unit="character"/>
<lb n="14"/><gap extent="unknown" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> pu<unclear>ṣkari</unclear>ṇī pū<unclear>rvveṇa</unclear> ribhu<unclear>pā</unclear>la-pū<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->rvva-datta-kṣetraṁ</supplied> <unclear>dakṣiṇena</unclear> <supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->pañca</supplied>
<lb n="15"/><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->kulya-vāpā</supplied> dattāḥ<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> <unclear>ta</unclear>d uttara-kālaṁ <unclear>saṁ</unclear>vyavahāribhir ddeva-bha<unclear>ktyā</unclear>numantavyā<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied><supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> <unclear>Uktaṁ</unclear> vyāsena</p>
          <lg met="anuṣṭubh" n="1">
            <l n="a">sva-dattāṁ para-dattā<lb break="no" n="16"/><unclear>m vā</unclear></l>
            <l n="b"><unclear>yo hareta</unclear> vasundharāM</l>
            <l n="c">sa viṣṭhā<unclear>yāṁ</unclear> k<sic>ri</sic>mi<unclear>r bbhūtvā</unclear></l>
            <l n="d">pi<unclear>tr̥</unclear>bhis sa<unclear>ha pacyate</unclear><!-- 
Basak prints viṣṭāyāṁ. Agrawala does likewise and emends to viṣṭhāyāṁ. Bhandarkar just prints the latter and I agree; I don't think the plates are in a good enough condition for us to assume an erronenous spelling. At the end of this line, clear vs unclear characters are shown in almost the exact opposite way in Basak (similarly Agrawala) than they are in Bhandarkar. I follow Basak; myself, I can't make out anything. 
--></l>
          </lg>
          <lg met="anuṣṭubh" n="2">
            <l n="a">pūrvva-dattāṁ dvijātibhyo</l>
            <l n="b"><lb n="17"/><unclear>yatnād rakṣa yu</unclear>dhiṣṭhira</l>
